{
  "How do you solve a radical equation?": "",
  "Isolate the radical, then raise both sides to the appropriate power": "",
  "Solve: √x = 7": "",
  "x = 49": "",
  "Solve: √(x + 5) = 3": "",
  "x + 5 = 9 → x = 4": "",
  "What are extraneous solutions in radical equations?": "",
  "False solutions introduced by squaring both sides": "",
  "Why must you check solutions?": "",
  "Squaring can introduce solutions that don't satisfy the original equation": "",
  "Solve: √(2x − 1) = 5": "",
  "2x − 1 = 25 → 2x = 26 → x = 13": "",
  "Does √x = −3 have a solution?": "",
  "No — the square root of a number cannot be negative": "",
  "Solve: ∛x = −2": "",
  "x = (−2)³ = −8": "",
  "Solve: √(3x + 1) = 4": "",
  "3x + 1 = 16 → 3x = 15 → x = 5": "",
  "Why does √x = −3 have no solution?": "",
  "Square roots are always non-negative; no real number squared gives a negative result under √": ""
